1390","after 1433":"po 1433","Bedfordshire, England":"Bedfordshire, Anglie","Hodnell, Warwickshire, England":"Hodnell, Warwickshire, Anglie","Tedburn St Mary, Devon, England":"Tedburn St Mary, Devon, Anglie","Eaton Bray, Bedfordshire, England":"Eaton Bray, Bedfordshire, Anglie"},"da":{"1378–after 1433":"1378–efter 1433","1378–1433":"1378–1433","1380–1430":"1380–1430","1390–1477":"1390–1477","1408–1453":"1408–1453","–Male":"Afdød","–Female":"Afdød","1403":"1403","1378":"1378","1477":"1477","1433":"1433","1453":"1453","1430":"1430","1382":"1382","1408":"1408","1380":"1380","1390":"1390","after 1433":"efter 1433","Bedfordshire, England":"Bedfordshire, England","Hodnell, Warwickshire, England":"Hodnell, Warwickshire, England","Tedburn St Mary, Devon, England":"Tedburn St Mary, Devon, England","Eaton Bray, Bedfordshire, England":"Eaton Bray, Bedfordshire, England"},"nl":{"1378–after 1433":"1378–na 1433","1378–1433":"1378–1433","1380–1430":"1380–1430","1390–1477":"1390–1477","1408–1453":"1408–1453","–Male":"Overleden","–Female":"Overleden","1403":"1403","1378":"1378","1477":"1477","1433":"1433","1453":"1453","1430":"1430","1382":"1382","1408":"1408","1380":"1380","1390":"1390","after 1433":"na 1433","Bedfordshire, England":"Bedfordshire, England","Hodnell, Warwickshire, England":"Hodnell, Warwickshire, England","Tedburn St Mary, Devon, England":"Tedburn St Mary, Devon, England","Eaton Bray, Bedfordshire, England":"Eaton Bray, Bedfordshire, England"},"en":{"1378–after 1433":"1378–after 1433","1378–1433":"1378–1433","1380–1430":"1380–1430","1390–1477":"1390–1477","1408–1453":"1408–1453","–Male":"Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","1403":"1403","1378":"1378","1477":"1477","1433":"1433","1453":"1453","1430":"1430","1382":"1382","1408":"1408","1380":"1380","1390":"1390","after 1433":"after 1433","Bedfordshire, England":"Bedfordshire, England","Hodnell, Warwickshire, England":"Hodnell, Warwickshire, England","Tedburn St Mary, Devon, England":"Tedburn St Mary, Devon, England","Eaton Bray, Bedfordshire, England":"Eaton Bray, Bedfordshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Spencer","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Yorkshire): occupational name for someone who dispensed provisions or money, from Middle English <i>spenser(e)</i>, <i>spencer(e)</i> ‘household steward, butler, almoner’ (Anglo-Norman French <i>espenser</i>, Old French <i>despensier</i>). Compare   Spence   and   Spender  . There is some dispute about the origins of the Spencer family, whose most famous member in recent times was the late Princess of Wales, born Lady Diana Spencer (1961–97). Some sources say that they are descended from William the Conqueror's steward, Robert Despencer. What is clear is that by the 15th century they had become prosperous from sheep farming in Northamptonshire. Robert Spencer (died 1627) was said to be the wealthiest man in England. Their titles have included Earls of Sunderland and Earls Spencer; and through the female line the 5th Earl of Sunderland also became Duke of Marlborough in 1733. This connection was the result of the marriage, in 1700, of the 3rd Duke of Sunderland to the daughter of John Churchill, 1st Duke of Marlborough. The youngest son of this union, John Spencer (1708–46), was the father of the 1st Earl Spencer (1734–83)."],"variants":[{"name":"Spence","meanings":["English and Scottish: nickname for a servant employed in the pantry of a great house or monastery, from Middle English <i>spense</i>, <i>spence</i> ‘pantry, larder, storeroom’ (Old French <i>despense</i>, from a Late Latin derivative of <i>dispendere</i>, past participle <i>dispensus</i> ‘to weigh out or dispense’). Compare   Spencer  ."]},{"name":"Spenser","meanings":["English: variant of   Spencer  ."]},{"name":"Spender","meanings":["English:","occupational name or status name from Middle English <i>spender(e)</i>, <i>spendour</i> ‘steward, treasurer’, a shortened form of Middle English, Old French <i>despendour</i>, denoting someone who managed money or supplies. Compare   Spencer  .","alternatively, perhaps a nickname from Middle English <i>spender(e)</i>, <i>spendour</i> ‘spender (of money), spendthrift’."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":4,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Thomas Spencer was born in 1378, in Hodnell, Warwickshire, England as the son of Richard Spencer Combe and Alice Hody Heiress of Combe.. He married Margaret Smith in 1403. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died after 1433, in Eaton Bray, Bedfordshire, England."},"et":{"1378–after 1433":"1378–pärast 1433","1378–1433":"1378–1433","1380–1430":"1380–1430","1390–1477":"1390–1477","1408–1453":"1408–1453","–Male":"Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1403":"1403","1378":"1378","1477":"1477","1433":"1433","1453":"1453","1430":"1430","1382":"1382","1408":"1408","1380":"1380","1390":"1390","after 1433":"pärast 1433","Bedfordshire, England":"Bedfordshire, England","Hodnell, Warwickshire, England":"Hodnell, Warwickshire, England","Te